Analysis of Obesity Factors in the United States

Bryce Patterson

What is Obesity?¶

Obesity is the category for an individual with an above average Body Mass Index, or BMI for short. BMI is used to measure the ratio between height and weight of an individual, and it's calculated by dividing a person's weight by the square of their height. A high BMI generally indicates high body fatness, but it is not a diagnosis of one's body health. However, BMI can be quickly computed and is correlated with direct measurements of body fat, making it an efficient indicator of one's weight class.

Importance of Weight Control¶

Obesity is a "common, serious, and costly disease" according to the CDC and is growing in the United States. It can lead to a number of health complications if left unchecked, such as diabetes, strokes, and even cancer. Although obesity takes time to inflict damage, it's important to take steps that are consistent with a healthy lifestyle. This project will look for some of the factors that contribute to obesity in the U.S. and draw conclusions from these results.

Purpose of this project¶

This project is designed to take you through the entire data pipeline, which consists of five steps:

  1. Data Collection
  2. Data Processing
  3. Exploratory Analysis and Data Visualization
  4. Analysis, Hypothesis testing, and ML
  5. Insight and Policy Decision

Data Processing¶

Just from first glance there are quite a few problems with the dataset. Many of the columns are duplicated or only one value, and we may need to unmelt the data to be able to graph points equally.

First, let's drop all the columns that aren't necessary, then sort them by YearStart, LocationAbbr, and QuestionID.

That's a little better, but that's a lot of NaN values. Let's try to condense our data by merging all the data in each state for each question. We'll do this by adding columns for every kind of respondent type, and filling in the column as the data type for each respondent. Then we can keep one row and remove the rest.

In [4]:
new_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['YearStart', 'LocationAbbr', 'Question', 'Data_Value', 'Age(years)',
       'Education', 'Gender', 'Income', 'Race/Ethnicity', 'QuestionID',
       'Hispanic', 'Some college or technical school', '45 - 54',
       'Hawaiian/Pacific Islander', 'American Indian/Alaska Native',
       '$15,000 - $24,999', 'Non-Hispanic White', 'Male', 'College graduate',
       'Non-Hispanic Black', '35 - 44', 'Less than $15,000', 'Female',
       '$50,000 - $74,999', 'Other', '65 or older', '18 - 24',
       'Less than high school', '$75,000 or greater', '$35,000 - $49,999',
       '55 - 64', '2 or more races', 'Asian', '25 - 34', 'Data not reported',
       'High school graduate', '$25,000 - $34,999'])

for year in df["YearStart"].unique():
  for loc in df["LocationAbbr"].unique():
    for qid in df["QuestionID"].unique():
      beginning_index = -1
      for index, row in df[(df["YearStart"] == year) &
                              (df["LocationAbbr"] == loc) &
                              (df["QuestionID"] == qid)].iterrows():
        if beginning_index == -1:
          beginning_index = index
        if isinstance(row["Age(years)"], str):
          df.at[beginning_index, row["Age(years)"]] = row["Data_Value"]
        elif isinstance(row["Gender"], str):
          df.at[beginning_index, row["Gender"]] = row["Data_Value"]
        elif isinstance(row["Income"], str):
          df.at[beginning_index, row["Income"]] = row["Data_Value"]
        elif isinstance(row["Race/Ethnicity"], str):
          df.at[beginning_index, row["Race/Ethnicity"]] = row["Data_Value"]
        elif isinstance(row["Education"], str):
          df.at[beginning_index, row["Education"]] = row["Data_Value"]
      if beginning_index != -1:
        new_df.loc[len(new_df.index)] = df.loc[beginning_index]

All of our columns have been correctly sorted, but it looks like there are still some NaN values. NaN stands for Not a Number, and this means there is no data for this people group for this question. In the original dataset the author mentions this is generally due to insufficient sample size, so even though this is inconvenient it only further validates our results. We need to see where they are most common, and how we can fix them. We can do this by seeing how many NaN values are in a column, and what percent of the column that value is.

In [6]:

The first four columns have no missing data, which is very good since it means we can query any year, location, and question without the case of it not existing. However, there is a remarkably large amount of data missing from columns pertaining to Race/Ethnicity, even up to 94% of data missing in the case of Hawaiian/Pacific Islander. The plot below visualizes the disparities of NaN values in the dataset.

There are 7 columns that have a NaN percentage greater than 1%:

  • Hispanic
  • Hawaiian/Pacific Islander
  • American Indian/Alaska Native
  • Non-Hispanic White
  • Non-Hispanic Black
  • Other
  • 2 or more races

It should be pointed out that nearly all the other columns with 1% NaN percentage have the exact same number of NaN values: 26. This leads me to believe there are 26 faulty rows in the dataset, which we may have to fix. But first, we will have to get rid of the above columns. We cannot make any meaningful conclusions with such little information, and attempting to solve this by filling in the values with close guesses would unavoidably introduce substantial amounts of bias into our model.

I believe there is such little information in these columns simply because fewer people chose to share their race when being questioned for this dataset. There are also fewer American Indians and Hawaiians inside the U.S. than other ethnicities, which may be why they are the columns with the most missing data. This is just conjecture, but it might be an interesting question to explore in another project.

Since there are too many states to be able to plot them all out, we will only focus on the data values for the US as a whole. This way we don't have to worry about a few states with missing data and we get a good representation of the country as if we had plotted the states values individually.

Each one of the questions has a unique ID to go along with it. Here is what each ID links to:

  • Q018: Percent of adults who report consuming fruit less than one time daily
  • Q019: Percent of adults who report consuming vegetables less than one time daily
  • Q036: Percent of adults aged 18 years and older who have obesity
  • Q037: Percent of adults aged 18 years and older who have an overweight classification
  • Q043: Percent of adults who achieve at least 150 minutes a week of moderate-intensity aerobic physical activity or 75 minutes a week of vigorous-intensity aerobic activity (or an equivalent combination)
  • Q044: Percent of adults who achieve at least 150 minutes a week of moderate-intensity aerobic physical activity or 75 minutes a week of vigorous-intensity aerobic physical activity and engage in muscle-strengthening activities on 2 or more days a week
  • Q045: Percent of adults who achieve at least 300 minutes a week of moderate-intensity aerobic physical activity or 150 minutes a week of vigorous-intensity aerobic activity (or an equivalent combination)
  • Q046: Percent of adults who engage in muscle-strengthening activities on 2 or more days a week
  • Q047: Percent of adults who engage in no leisure-time physical activity

First let's create a function to easily plot out each question and its respondents answers, then we can visualize the data.

In [108]:
# final_df[final_df["18 - 24"].isna()].sort_values(["Year", "Location", "QuestionID"], ascending=True)
def make_plot(QuestionID:str, Location:str):

  obes_df = final_df[(final_df["QuestionID"] == QuestionID) & (final_df["Location"] == Location)]
  sorted_rows = obes_df.sort_values(["Year"], ascending=True)
  plt.figure(figsize=(18, 4))

  # Plot for Age groups
  plt.subplot(1, 4, 1)
  plt.title('By Age Groups')
  plt.xlabel('Year')
  plt.ylabel('Percent of Population')

  line1 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["18 - 24"], label='18 - 24')
  line2 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["25 - 34"], label='25 - 34')
  line3 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["35 - 44"], label='35 - 44')
  line4 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["45 - 54"], label='45 - 54')
  line5 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["55 - 64"], label='55 - 64')
  plt.legend(loc='upper left')

  # Plot for Education 
  plt.subplot(1, 4, 2)
  plt.title('By Education Level')
  plt.xlabel('Year')
  plt.ylabel('Percent of Population')
  
  line1 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["Less than high school"], label='Less than high school')
  line2 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["High school graduate"], label = 'High school graduate')
  line3 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["Some college or technical school"], label = 'Some college/tech school')
  line4 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows["College graduate"], label = 'College graduate')
  plt.legend(loc='upper left')
  
  # Plot for Income
  plt.subplot(1, 4, 3)
  plt.title('By Income')
  plt.xlabel('Year')
  plt.ylabel('Percent of Population')

  line1 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['Less than $15,000'], label = '$15k<')
  line2 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['$15,000 - $24,999'], label = '$15k-24k')
  line3 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['$25,000 - $34,999'], label = '$25k-34k')
  line4 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['$35,000 - $49,999'], label = '$35k-49k')
  line5 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['$50,000 - $74,999'], label = '$50k-74k')
  line6 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['$75,000 or greater'], label = '$75k+')
  plt.legend(loc='upper left')

  # Plot for Sex
  plt.subplot(1, 4, 4)
  plt.title('By Sex')
  plt.xlabel('Year')
  plt.ylabel('Percent of Population')

  line1 = plt.plot(sorted_rows["Year"], sorted_rows['Male'], label = 'Male')
  line2 = plt.plot(sorted_rows['Year'], sorted_rows['Female'], label = 'Female')
  plt.legend(loc='upper left')
  plt.show()
